# Visual Hierarchy

> **Reference**: This guide extends the [UX/UI Design Principles](ux-ui.mdc). Make sure you're familiar with core UX/UI principles before diving into visual hierarchy specifics.

## üìã Overview

Visual hierarchy is the arrangement and presentation of elements in order of importance, guiding users' attention through content naturally and efficiently. Effective visual hierarchy uses size, color, contrast, spacing, typography, and layout to create a clear path for the eye to follow.

**Goal**: Help users understand what's most important, what to read first, and where to look next.

## üéØ Core Principles of Visual Hierarchy

### 1. Size and Scale
Larger elements naturally draw more attention:
- Headlines > Subheadings > Body text
- Primary buttons > Secondary buttons
- Hero images > Supporting images

### 2. Color and Contrast
High contrast elements stand out:
- Dark text on light backgrounds (or vice versa)
- Accent colors for important elements
- Muted colors for less important content

### 3. Spacing and Proximity
Related elements should be grouped together:
- Items close together appear related
- Generous whitespace creates separation
- Consistent spacing creates visual rhythm

### 4. Typography
Font characteristics convey importance:
- Weight (bold vs regular vs light)
- Size (large vs small)
- Style (italic, uppercase, decorative)
- Font family (display vs text)

### 5. Position and Layout
Natural reading patterns:
- Top-to-bottom: Users read from top first
- Left-to-right: Western languages flow left to right
- F-pattern: Users scan in F-shaped pattern
- Z-pattern: Eye movement for less text-heavy pages

